 March 2020|website=The News & Observer|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320190055/https://www.newsobserver.com/news/coronavirus/article241363186.html|archive-date=March 20, 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Ohio: The state reported its first coronavirus death, Mark Wagoner Sr, a 76-year-old attorney from [[Lucas County, Ohio|Lucas County]] in the [[Toledo, Ohio|Toledo]] area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.10tv.com/article/dewine-says-1st-ohio-coronavirus-death-76-year-old-man-2020-mar|title=DeWine says 1st Ohio coronavirus death is 76-year-old man|date=March 20, 2020|website=10tv.com|access-date=March 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321014412/https://www.10tv.com/article/dewine-says-1st-ohio-coronavirus-death-76-year-old-man-2020-mar|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The state had a total of 169 cases. Governor DeWine announces that senior centers and senior daycare centers will close.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbc4i.com/community/coronavirus-in-ohio-governor-odh-plan-friday-afternoon-update/|title=Coronavirus in Ohio Friday update: 169 cases, first death confirmed|date=March 20, 2020|website=nbc4i.com|access-date=March 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321015231/https://www.nbc4i.com/community/coronavirus-in-ohio-governor-odh-plan-friday-afternoon-update/|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Tennessee: 15 recovery cases are confirmed in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/health/2020/03/20/coronavirus-nashville-15-patients-have-recovered-virus/2885351001/|title='Encouraging': 15 people in Nashville recovered from coronavirus, health officials say|first=Brett|last=Kelman|website=The Tennessean|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> However, the health department confirmed the state's first death of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/health/2020/03/20/first-coronavirus-death-tennessee-reported-nashville-davidson-county/2886440001/|title=Nashville health department reports Tennessee's first coronavirus death|first=Emily R.|last=West|website=The Tennessean|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n*Texas: Dallas mega-church preacher [[Robert Jeffress]] agrees to move his Sunday services online.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-fears-force-dallas-megachurch-pastor-jeffress-to-move-services-online-211141698.html Dallas megachurch pastor Jeffress capitulates to coronavirus warnings, moves services online] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320215751/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-fears-force-dallas-megachurch-pastor-jeffress-to-move-services-online-211141698.html |date=March 20, 2020 }} by Alexander Nazaryan, Yahoo News, 20 March 2020</ref>\n*Virginia: Governor Northam activated Virginia National Guard. The state announced they have 114 cases of COVID-19, with 20 hospitalizations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wydaily.com/local-news/2020/03/20/national-guard-activated-james-city-county-coronavirus-positive-cases-jumps-to-19-williamsburg-has-four-the-state-114/|title=National Guard activated: James City County coronavirus positive cases jumps to 19; Williamsburg has four; the state, 114|last=Marsigliano|first=Julia|date=2020-03-20|website=Williamsburg Yorktown Daily|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321020357/https://wydaily.com/local-news/2020/03/20/national-guard-activated-james-city-county-coronavirus-positive-cases-jumps-to-19-williamsburg-has-four-the-state-114/|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 21====\n*Vice President Mike Pence and his wife test negative for COVID-19 infection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fox8.com/news/coronavirus/vice-president-mike-pence-and-wife-test-negative-for-covid-19-white-house-says/|title=Vice President Mike Pence and wife test negative for COVID-19, White House says|date=2020-03-22|website=fox8.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n*Florida: Governor DeSantis is considering a new strategy to put positive COVID-19 patients into isolation shelters such as abandoned convention centers and hotels instead of returning the patients to their home where they can infect their own family. Cases in Florida reached 763 presumptive positive cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/coronavirus/article241401496.html|title=DeSantis considers new strategy in Florida coronavirus fight: isolation shelters|last=Mower|first=Lawrence|date=March 21, 2020|website=Miami Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Michigan: Four more deaths from coronavirus are reported, bringing to total number of deaths in the state to eight.<ref>{{cite web |title=Macomb County officials announce 8th COVID-19 death in Michigan |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/03/22/watch-live-macomb-county-officials-hold-press-conference-on-coronavirus/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Also, the total number of cases of coronavirus in the state rises to 807.<ref>{{cite web |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases continue to rise, state total now 807 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/03/21/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-continue-to-rise-state-total-now-787/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> \n*Minnesota: The state confirmed the first death due to the virus; the patient was from Ramsey County and was in their 80's. The patient had contracted the virus from a confirmed case.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.health.state.mn.us/news/pressrel/2020/covid032120.html|title=Health officials confirm first death due to COVID-19 in Minnesota|accessdate= March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n* Ohio: The state has 247 confirmed cases of COVID-19. Facilities providing daycare and assistance for adults with developmental disabilities are closed unless they serve 10 people or less.<ref>{{cite web 